WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.810 --> 00:00:05.336
<i>My parents died
when I was very young,</i>


2
00:00:05.450 --> 00:00:08.135
<i>so there's no one to ask
where it came from.</i>


3
00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:11.974
<i>I've grown accustomed
to being on my own.</i>


4
00:00:12.330 --> 00:00:15.095
<i>Some say even too accustomed.</i>

5
00:00:16.130 --> 00:00:18.781
<i>Too independent.</i>

6
00:00:58.890 --> 00:00:59.891
(URGES HORSE)

7
00:01:36.290 --> 00:01:38.611
(DOG BARKING)

8
00:01:51.370 --> 00:01:52.701
GABRIEL: Miss!

9
00:01:56.210 --> 00:01:57.496
Miss!

10
00:01:58.250 --> 00:01:59.820
(SHEEP BLEATING)

11
00:02:10.770 --> 00:02:11.817
(PANTING)

12
00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:14.740
My scarf.

13
00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:16.695
I lost it.

14
00:02:17.810 --> 00:02:19.460
You must be Farmer Oak.

15
00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:21.180
Gabriel, yes.

16
00:02:21.570 --> 00:02:23.299
My aunt's told me
about you.


17
00:02:23.370 --> 00:02:25.179
I'm working on her farm
for the winter.


18
00:02:28.730 --> 00:02:30.334
This is your land.

19
00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:34.012
I'm trespassing.

20
00:02:34.090 --> 00:02:35.933
You're welcome here.

21
00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:50.375
Good afternoon,
Farmer Oak.


22
00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:52.579
Good afternoon, miss.

23
00:03:12.450 --> 00:03:13.895
(GABRIEL WHISTLES)

24
00:03:22.570 --> 00:03:24.060
GABRIEL: Come by, George.

25
00:03:24.450 --> 00:03:27.977
George, away!
Enough, George!


26
00:03:28.090 --> 00:03:29.580
(YOUNG GEORGE BARKING)
Enough!


27
00:03:30.650 --> 00:03:32.652
Stand. Stand.

28
00:03:33.050 --> 00:03:34.461
George, stand.

29
00:03:34.930 --> 00:03:36.056
(BARKING CONTINUES)

30
00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:37.416
Away!

31
00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:38.971
Away!

32
00:03:40.130 --> 00:03:42.451
George, away!

33
00:03:44.250 --> 00:03:46.173
He doesn't know when to stop,
Young George.


34
00:03:46.650 --> 00:03:48.061
What's this one called?

35
00:03:48.130 --> 00:03:49.370
Old George.

36
00:03:49.450 --> 00:03:50.736
(BATHSHEBA LAUGHS)

37
00:03:52.130 --> 00:03:53.575
Old George.

38
00:03:54.010 --> 00:03:55.580
So you find me
amusing, do you?


39
00:03:55.650 --> 00:03:57.937
(YOUNG GEORGE CONTINUES BARKING)

40
00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:07.851
(WHINNIES)

41
00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:47.532
Goodness,
it's Mr. Oak.


42
00:04:58.370 --> 00:05:00.690
MRS. HURST: ...and after that
she was gonna be a governess.


43
00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:02.141
But she was far too wild.

44
00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:04.059
Always has been.

45
00:05:04.130 --> 00:05:05.131
Oh!

46
00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:15.732
Miss Bathsheba Everdene.

47
00:05:16.690 --> 00:05:18.818
I've brought you a lamb.

48
00:05:19.330 --> 00:05:21.219
Oh!
(LAMB BLEATING)


49
00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:26.698
Thank you, Mr. Oak.
He's such a dear thing.


50
00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:29.057
He's come too soon
and won't last the winter,


51
00:05:29.170 --> 00:05:31.332
so I thought you'd
like to rear it instead.


52
00:05:31.730 --> 00:05:33.937
Thank you,
that's very kind.


53
00:05:34.770 --> 00:05:36.932
I'll make some tea.

54
00:05:40.010 --> 00:05:41.694
The lamb is not
why I came.


55
00:05:41.850 --> 00:05:43.534
Go on.

56
00:05:45.290 --> 00:05:46.337
(CHUCKLES)

57
00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:49.016
Well, Miss Everdene,
I wanted to ask...


58
00:05:49.610 --> 00:05:51.374
Would you like
to marry me?


59
00:05:54.610 --> 00:05:56.214
I've never asked
anyone before.


60
00:05:56.450 --> 00:05:57.690
(CHUCKLES)

61
00:05:58.410 --> 00:05:59.411
No.

62
00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:02.379
I should hope not.

63
00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:04.896
Well...

64
00:06:05.930 --> 00:06:08.456
Perhaps I, erm, I should...

65
00:06:10.450 --> 00:06:11.736
Perhaps I should leave.
Mr. Oak,


66
00:06:11.810 --> 00:06:13.574
there are things to consider.

67
00:06:14.970 --> 00:06:16.734
Is someone waiting for you?

68
00:06:17.050 --> 00:06:20.213
No, but that doesn't
mean I'll marry you.


69
00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:22.781
Good day to you, then.

70
00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:33.420
Mr. Oak!

71
00:06:34.130 --> 00:06:37.293
Mr. Oak! Wait!

72
00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:42.821
I didn't say I wouldn't
marry you, either.


73
00:06:43.090 --> 00:06:44.979
(PANTING)

74
00:06:45.090 --> 00:06:46.819
I haven't ever really
thought about it.


75
00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:50.573
I have 100 acres
and 200 sheep.


76
00:06:52.330 --> 00:06:55.254
If I pay off the money,
the farm is ours.


77
00:06:56.770 --> 00:06:59.011
You could have a piano
in a year or two.


78
00:06:59.130 --> 00:07:02.452
Flowers and birds
and a frame for cucumbers.


79
00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:04.295
A baby or two.

80
00:07:04.450 --> 00:07:05.611
Mr. Oak...
Or more.


81
00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:08.773
I will always
be there for you.


82
00:07:10.490 --> 00:07:12.618
Mr. Oak, I don't
want a husband.


83
00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:15.810
I'd hate to be
some man's property.


84
00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:18.740
I shouldn't mind being
a bride at a wedding


85
00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:20.778
if I could be one
without getting a husband.


86
00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:23.053
That's stupid talk.

87
00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:26.977
You are better off
than I, Mr. Oak.


88
00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:29.691
I have an education
and nothing more.


89
00:07:29.850 --> 00:07:31.454
You could do much,
much better than me.


90
00:07:31.530 --> 00:07:33.020
That's not the reason.

91
00:07:38.050 --> 00:07:39.170
I'm too independent for you.

92
00:07:39.290 --> 00:07:40.291
(LAUGHS)

93
00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:42.211
If I ever were to marry,

94
00:07:42.290 --> 00:07:43.530
I'd want somebody to tame me

95
00:07:43.650 --> 00:07:45.300
and you'd never
be able to do it.


96
00:07:47.130 --> 00:07:49.212
You'd grow to despise me.

97
00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:53.180
I would not.

98
00:07:55.370 --> 00:07:56.701
Ever.

99
00:08:01.330 --> 00:08:03.571
Good-bye, Miss Everdene.

100
00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:31.778
(OLD GEORGE WHINING SOFTLY)

101
00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:35.532
(YOUNG GEORGE BARKING OUTSIDE)

102
00:08:37.010 --> 00:08:38.421
(WHINING CONTINUES)

103
00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:47.895
(BARKING)

104
00:08:49.050 --> 00:08:50.051
(GROWLING)

105
00:08:51.690 --> 00:08:53.215
(SHEEP BLEATING)

106
00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:57.537
(BARKING CONTINUES)

107
00:09:03.570 --> 00:09:05.095
(BARKS)
What is it, old boy?


108
00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:06.621
(WHINING)

109
00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:09.620
Stay here.

110
00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:15.095
Stay here, Old George.

111
00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:16.979
(BARKING)
Stay here.


112
00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:27.935
George!

113
00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:33.494
(YOUNG GEORGE BARKING IN DISTANCE)

114
00:09:40.170 --> 00:09:42.252
George!

115
00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:45.618
(DISTANT BLEATING AND BARKING)

116
00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:01.655
(BLEATING FRANTICALLY)

117
00:10:02.850 --> 00:10:03.931
(BARKING)

118
00:10:09.210 --> 00:10:11.133
(PANTING)

119
00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:16.019
(BARKING CONTINUES)

120
00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:30.300
No!

121
00:10:58.370 --> 00:11:00.577
(SCREAMING)

122
00:11:15.250 --> 00:11:16.900
(GUNSHOT)
(THUD)


123
00:11:37.930 --> 00:11:39.136
It's all yours.

124
00:11:50.370 --> 00:11:52.577
We take no pleasure in this.

125
00:11:53.450 --> 00:11:54.531
(PANTING)

126
00:11:54.610 --> 00:11:56.738
BAILIFF: We wish
you well, Mr. Oak.


127
00:12:11.770 --> 00:12:12.976
MRS. HURST: Bathsheba.

128
00:12:17.770 --> 00:12:19.295
What is it?

129
00:12:19.930 --> 00:12:23.616
My love. It's your
poor uncle's will.


130
00:12:24.570 --> 00:12:26.140
What does it say?

131
00:12:27.610 --> 00:12:28.975
Read it.

132
00:12:30.170 --> 00:12:31.615
Read!

133
00:12:33.530 --> 00:12:37.455
He's left you everything.
It's all yours.


134
00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:39.530
Oh!

135
00:12:40.330 --> 00:12:42.298
Oh, my goodness.

136
00:12:43.850 --> 00:12:46.012
Take care,
you hear.


137
00:12:54.170 --> 00:12:55.535
Walk on.

138
00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:02.541
Bye.

139
00:13:21.490 --> 00:13:22.776
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

140
00:13:22.850 --> 00:13:25.057
So who will
join us, lads?


141
00:13:25.850 --> 00:13:27.340
Which one of you fine boys

142
00:13:27.410 --> 00:13:29.014
will put on
the scarlet uniform


143
00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:32.492
and proudly serve
his Queen and country?


144
00:13:33.490 --> 00:13:35.015
See the world.

145
00:13:36.170 --> 00:13:39.014
Form an orderly line,
gentlemen, at the front.


146
00:13:39.330 --> 00:13:40.331
This gentleman
in the straw hat,


147
00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:41.457
step forward, sir.

148
00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:43.180
That's my sweetheart,
right there.


149
00:13:43.650 --> 00:13:47.018
You, sir,
next to the pretty lady.


150
00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:49.538
There's a good strong
figure of a man.


151
00:13:49.930 --> 00:13:51.261
Join us, sir.

152
00:13:51.690 --> 00:13:53.613
Go on. You'd make
a fine soldier.


153
00:13:53.690 --> 00:13:55.579
Always room in the ranks for
a gentleman of your caliber.


154
00:13:55.690 --> 00:13:57.260
FANNY: It's a roof
over your head. Food.


155
00:13:59.850 --> 00:14:02.057
DOGGETT: Who wants
a fine wage?


156
00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:03.535
Excuse me.

157
00:14:03.610 --> 00:14:06.295
You might try Weatherbury.
If you're looking for work,


158
00:14:06.370 --> 00:14:08.498
there's a farm there
needs all the help it can get.


159
00:14:08.570 --> 00:14:10.220
DOGGETT: Yes.
The young lad there.


160
00:14:10.290 --> 00:14:12.292
I will. Thank you.

161
00:14:12.370 --> 00:14:13.650
DOGGETT: And your
friend as well.


162
00:14:13.690 --> 00:14:15.533
You should have a cloak
for a day like this.


163
00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:18.940
FANNY: Francis
will take care of me.


164
00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:23.134
We are to be married soon.

165
00:14:24.090 --> 00:14:25.455
Good-bye.

166
00:14:25.570 --> 00:14:27.174
DOGGETT: Come on,
a decent wage.


167
00:14:27.250 --> 00:14:28.820
Make your family proud.

168
00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:32.093
Food, shelter.
Who will join us?


169
00:15:11.130 --> 00:15:12.973
(DISTANT SHOUTING, INDISTINCT)

170
00:15:18.770 --> 00:15:20.659
(SHOUTING CONTINUES)

171
00:15:24.970 --> 00:15:27.291
FARMHAND #1: Go and wake up
the other farms!


172
00:15:27.370 --> 00:15:29.577
Get them down here!
We need more hands!


173
00:15:29.650 --> 00:15:30.811
FARMHAND #2: We need
more men now!


174
00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:31.931
Wake them up!

175
00:15:32.690 --> 00:15:35.216
FARMHAND #1: Go and get
the Smith brothers first.


176
00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:37.810
FARMHAND #3: Protect yourself,
the fire's spreading!


177
00:15:37.930 --> 00:15:39.011
(FARMHANDS COUGHING)

178
00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:40.495
Who's in charge here?

179
00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:43.898
We're losing the ricks!
(COUGHING) The rick is lost.


180
00:15:44.450 --> 00:15:46.214
We need to save the barn.
Come on, help me!


181
00:15:47.010 --> 00:15:50.253
Come on, get some more water!
Get some more water!


182
00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:51.331
(FARMHANDS CLAMORING)

183
00:15:51.450 --> 00:15:53.976
We need to push
this out. Come on!


184
00:15:54.050 --> 00:15:55.336
Heave!

185
00:15:57.450 --> 00:15:59.134
ALL: Heave!

186
00:15:59.450 --> 00:16:00.815
Heave!

187
00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:04.616
GABRIEL: Come on, push!

188
00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:06.818
(MEN GRUNTING)

189
00:16:13.690 --> 00:16:15.499
(FARMHANDS CONTINUE SHOUTING)

190
00:16:27.330 --> 00:16:30.015
FARMHAND #1: Everybody out!
Everybody out!


191
00:16:34.370 --> 00:16:36.657
FARMHAND #2: Water!
More over here!


192
00:16:36.730 --> 00:16:37.777
The barn's going up!

193
00:16:37.850 --> 00:16:40.171
FARMHAND #3: Get the sacks out,
the roof's about to go!


194
00:16:44.210 --> 00:16:46.019
(PANTING)

195
00:16:56.530 --> 00:16:58.373
What's he doing up there?

196
00:16:58.450 --> 00:17:01.056
OLDER MAN: We lose the barn,
we lose everything.


197
00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:28.220
(PANTING)

198
00:17:32.570 --> 00:17:34.413
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

199
00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:43.856
JACOB: Joseph,
bring those brooms over


200
00:17:43.930 --> 00:17:45.580
and let's get
this sorted out.


201
00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:49.414
Look sharp, men,
the farmer's here.


202
00:18:03.610 --> 00:18:05.612
Mr. Oak, is that you?

203
00:18:10.490 --> 00:18:11.935
Perhaps you want
a shepherd, ma'am?


204
00:18:15.970 --> 00:18:18.621
I owe you an immense
debt, Mr. Oak.


205
00:18:19.210 --> 00:18:21.497
If I'd have lost all of this,
I'd have lost my farm.


206
00:18:21.610 --> 00:18:22.657
Your farm?

207
00:18:23.130 --> 00:18:24.370
My inheritance.

208
00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:27.374
My home, too, for a while
when my parents died.


209
00:18:28.690 --> 00:18:31.534
When my uncle passed away,
he left it to me.


210
00:18:32.610 --> 00:18:35.295
Of course,
it's a little ragged now,


211
00:18:36.130 --> 00:18:38.974
but this once used to be
the finest farm for miles.


212
00:18:39.130 --> 00:18:41.656
And I intend
to make it so again.


213
00:18:43.130 --> 00:18:44.655
Perhaps you find
the idea preposterous.


214
00:18:45.330 --> 00:18:47.810
I no longer
have that luxury.


215
00:18:49.490 --> 00:18:52.221
I'm truly sorry to hear
of your loss, Mr. Oak,


216
00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:53.780
but if our
reversal of fortune


217
00:18:53.850 --> 00:18:55.261
causes you any embarrassment...

218
00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:57.737
Not at all, ma'am.

219
00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:04.891
BATHSHEBA: Billy Smallbury?

220
00:19:06.970 --> 00:19:08.734
Joseph Poorgrass?

221
00:19:09.250 --> 00:19:10.376
WOMAN: Go on, Joseph.

222
00:19:10.530 --> 00:19:11.691
MAN: Go on, lad.

223
00:19:11.810 --> 00:19:13.414
(WHISPERS) Hat off.

224
00:19:14.650 --> 00:19:16.220
And what do you do, Joseph?

225
00:19:16.370 --> 00:19:17.974
I does general things.

226
00:19:18.050 --> 00:19:19.290
And in spring
I shoot the rooks


227
00:19:19.370 --> 00:19:20.530
and help at pig killing, sir.

228
00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:21.571
(FAINT LAUGHTER)

229
00:19:21.690 --> 00:19:22.737
I mean ma'am.

230
00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:28.096
7 and 9 pence.
And another 9 because I'm new.


231
00:19:28.170 --> 00:19:30.013
Thank you, ma'am.

232
00:19:34.210 --> 00:19:36.212
Now, Fanny Robbin?

233
00:19:38.530 --> 00:19:40.612
Where is Fanny Robbin?

234
00:19:41.410 --> 00:19:42.411
Where is she?

235
00:19:43.570 --> 00:19:45.732
She's run away, ma'am.

236
00:19:46.370 --> 00:19:48.179
She's gone off
with a soldier, ma'am.


237
00:19:48.250 --> 00:19:50.412
Not a soldier, a sergeant.

238
00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:56.215
Bailiff Pennyways?

239
00:19:56.370 --> 00:19:57.815
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

240
00:20:01.210 --> 00:20:03.816
Here is 10 shillings
and a further 10.


241
00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:05.780
(SOFTLY) Why?

242
00:20:06.730 --> 00:20:09.301
This ends our association.
You are dismissed.


243
00:20:09.730 --> 00:20:11.255
I beg pardon, miss?

244
00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:12.371
When my uncle was alive,

245
00:20:12.490 --> 00:20:14.618
this was a fine,
productive farm.


246
00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:17.417
Since his death,
it has fallen into ruin.


247
00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:20.450
I can only assume...
Now see here, miss.


248
00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:21.616
You can't get rid
of people like that.


249
00:20:21.730 --> 00:20:22.731
I have resolved
to have no bailiff at all,


250
00:20:22.810 --> 00:20:23.857
I have decided
to manage everything.


251
00:20:23.930 --> 00:20:25.932
Mr. Pennyways, if you'll
listen to me for a moment.


252
00:20:26.050 --> 00:20:28.974
Mr. Pennyways, a fire
threatened to destroy the barn


253
00:20:29.090 --> 00:20:31.252
and you are
nowhere to be found.


254
00:20:36.130 --> 00:20:39.179
I have no use for a man
like you, Mr. Pennyways.


255
00:20:40.250 --> 00:20:41.297
You are dismissed.

256
00:20:50.810 --> 00:20:52.690
PENNYWAYS: Get out
while you can, if I were you.


257
00:20:54.850 --> 00:20:56.261
(ALL MURMURING)

258
00:21:03.770 --> 00:21:05.613
Now you've all met
our new shepherd, Mr. Oak.


259
00:21:07.490 --> 00:21:09.618
You understand
your duties, Mr. Oak?


260
00:21:10.810 --> 00:21:12.812
If I don't, I'll ask, ma'am.

261
00:21:18.610 --> 00:21:21.819
From now on, you have
a mistress, not a master.


262
00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:24.050
I don't yet know
my talents in farming,


263
00:21:24.130 --> 00:21:25.620
but I shall do my best.

264
00:21:26.610 --> 00:21:27.975
Don't suppose,
because I'm a woman,


265
00:21:28.050 --> 00:21:29.131
I don't know
the difference between


266
00:21:29.210 --> 00:21:30.860
bad goings-on and good.

267
00:21:30.970 --> 00:21:33.132
I shall be up
before you're awake.


268
00:21:33.730 --> 00:21:35.494
I shall be a-field
before you are up.


269
00:21:36.370 --> 00:21:39.135
It is my intention
to astonish you all.


270
00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:43.655
Back to work, please.

271
00:21:45.970 --> 00:21:47.813
(MURMURING RESUMES)

272
00:21:56.250 --> 00:21:58.173
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

273
00:22:03.010 --> 00:22:04.899
Perhaps I should
wait here?


274
00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:06.250
No.

275
00:22:06.850 --> 00:22:10.332
Nonsense, Liddy.
You're my companion.


276
00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:11.411
All of these?

277
00:22:11.610 --> 00:22:12.611
All of them.

278
00:22:14.890 --> 00:22:15.891
Head high, Liddy.

279
00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:17.853
If they stare,
do not hesitate.


280
00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:21.092
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

281
00:22:25.170 --> 00:22:27.776
Remember, we have as much
right to be here as anyone.


282
00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:33.370
Good morning.

283
00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:36.138
(MEN CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY)

284
00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:40.374
(CHATTERING STOPS)

285
00:22:50.210 --> 00:22:51.780
Liddy, if you
lay things out.


286
00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:53.455
Yes, miss.

287
00:22:54.570 --> 00:22:58.131
Gentlemen, shall we
get back to business?


288
00:22:59.650 --> 00:23:01.459
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

289
00:23:07.730 --> 00:23:09.095
There you go, sir.

290
00:23:09.250 --> 00:23:10.850
If you feel it,
you can feel the quality.


291
00:23:11.410 --> 00:23:12.411
This is fine
grain, miss.


292
00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:13.537
Thank you.

293
00:23:16.250 --> 00:23:18.412
Perhaps we should
leave, miss.


294
00:23:21.770 --> 00:23:23.499
But none of it
as good as this lot.


295
00:23:23.570 --> 00:23:24.731
It's good stuff,
I'll grant you that.


296
00:23:24.930 --> 00:23:26.170
Well, it's up to you.
If you wanna go elsewhere...


297
00:23:26.250 --> 00:23:27.331
No, no, no...

298
00:23:27.410 --> 00:23:28.616
Farmer Stone?

299
00:23:29.250 --> 00:23:32.777
It's Miss Everdene.
Farmer Everdene's niece.


300
00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:36.617
He talked about you
with such great admiration.


301
00:23:39.410 --> 00:23:41.094
Of course, you're welcome
to try elsewhere,


302
00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:44.379
but I think you'll find the
grain as good as it's ever been.


303
00:23:47.170 --> 00:23:48.501
(SNIFFS)

304
00:23:48.930 --> 00:23:50.341
Mr. Stone?
How much?


305
00:23:50.450 --> 00:23:52.293
£5 a quarter.

306
00:23:52.450 --> 00:23:54.339
£3-10 shillings.

307
00:23:54.610 --> 00:23:55.810
It's the same grain,
Mr. Stone.


308
00:23:55.850 --> 00:23:58.171
You paid my uncle £5.

309
00:23:58.290 --> 00:24:00.133
£3-10.

310
00:24:02.010 --> 00:24:04.377
BATHSHEBA: This gentleman
will pay me the proper price.


311
00:24:06.970 --> 00:24:08.813
MAN: Apparently not, no.

312
00:24:09.290 --> 00:24:10.337
£4.

313
00:24:10.450 --> 00:24:11.451
£4-10.

314
00:24:11.610 --> 00:24:13.055
£4-05.

315
00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:15.735
Perhaps I should move on.

316
00:24:16.530 --> 00:24:18.737
Liddy, would you help me
with this gentleman?


317
00:24:18.810 --> 00:24:20.221
Of course.

318
00:24:20.970 --> 00:24:22.972
Perhaps you'd
like a sample?


319
00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:25.333
How much?
£5 a quarter.


320
00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:27.814
Very well.

321
00:24:29.810 --> 00:24:31.539
£4-10.

322
00:24:33.130 --> 00:24:34.700
(PEOPLE APPLAUDING)

323
00:24:40.650 --> 00:24:42.493
(CHURCH ORGAN PLAYING)

324
00:24:42.570 --> 00:24:46.017
<i>Jerusalem the golden</i>

325
00:24:46.170 --> 00:24:51.210
<i>With milk and honey blest</i>

326
00:24:51.850 --> 00:24:57.334
<i>Beneath thy contemplation</i>

327
00:24:57.690 --> 00:25:02.696
<i>Sink heart and voice oppressed</i>

328
00:25:03.610 --> 00:25:08.741
He's rich, he's handsome.
He sends the local girls mad.


329
00:25:09.170 --> 00:25:12.652
The Taylor sisters
worked on him for two years.


330
00:25:12.730 --> 00:25:14.892
Jane Perkins spent £20
on new clothes


331
00:25:15.010 --> 00:25:16.091
and might as well have

332
00:25:16.210 --> 00:25:18.258
thrown the money
out the window.


333
00:25:20.450 --> 00:25:24.296
It's said, when he was young,
his sweetheart jilted him.


334
00:25:26.050 --> 00:25:28.052
People always say that.

335
00:25:28.530 --> 00:25:31.693
Women don't jilt men.
Men jilt us.


336
00:25:32.210 --> 00:25:34.531
Did someone jilt you, miss?

337
00:25:34.890 --> 00:25:36.779
Certainly not.

338
00:25:40.210 --> 00:25:42.372
A man did ask
to marry me once.


339
00:25:42.450 --> 00:25:43.736
Some time ago.

340
00:25:44.130 --> 00:25:46.610
But I was too restless
to be tied down.


341
00:25:46.730 --> 00:25:50.052
What a luxury,
to have a choice.


342
00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:55.301
"Kiss my foot, sir, my face
is for mouths of consequence."


343
00:25:55.410 --> 00:25:57.333
It wasn't
like that at all.


344
00:25:58.250 --> 00:25:59.581
LIDDY: Why?

345
00:26:00.650 --> 00:26:02.140
Did you love him?

346
00:26:02.650 --> 00:26:05.096
No, but I rather liked him.

347
00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:08.411
Anyway, it's impossible now.

348
00:26:08.490 --> 00:26:09.730
(CONGREGATION CONTINUES SINGING)

349
00:26:11.490 --> 00:26:12.616
(SQUAWKING)

350
00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:16.176
(GUNSHOT)

351
00:26:22.130 --> 00:26:23.416
Mr. Boldwood.

352
00:26:23.930 --> 00:26:25.091
Don't shoot me, please.

353
00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:28.091
I had no intention
of shooting you.


354
00:26:30.450 --> 00:26:32.930
It's Miss Everdene.
Your neighbor.


355
00:26:34.290 --> 00:26:36.497
Farmer Everdene's niece.

356
00:26:39.690 --> 00:26:40.737
I'm managing the farm
alone now.


357
00:26:40.810 --> 00:26:41.811
Perhaps you've heard?

358
00:26:41.970 --> 00:26:44.337
Yes, I'm sure
you'll do very well.


359
00:26:46.050 --> 00:26:47.211
In the circumstances.

360
00:26:51.050 --> 00:26:54.418
Well, as you say,
we're neighbors.


361
00:26:54.490 --> 00:26:55.537
(CLICKS TONGUE)

362
00:26:55.610 --> 00:26:57.021
(HORSE GALLOPING)

363
00:27:07.210 --> 00:27:09.053
LIDDY: Look what
I've got here.


364
00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:11.291
What is it?

365
00:27:11.490 --> 00:27:12.491
Listen to this.

366
00:27:12.570 --> 00:27:14.334
"The rose is red
The violet blue


367
00:27:14.490 --> 00:27:17.494
"Carnation's sweet
And so are you"


368
00:27:19.330 --> 00:27:21.014
It's a Valentine's card.

369
00:27:21.170 --> 00:27:23.332
I'm going to send it
to Joseph Poorgrass


370
00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:26.095
just to see the look
of panic on his stupid face.


371
00:27:26.210 --> 00:27:29.054
Poor boy. It's a little bit
far-fetched, isn't it?


372
00:27:29.690 --> 00:27:32.341
What about
Mr. Oak, then?


373
00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:35.061
No. Not Mr. Oak.

374
00:27:36.490 --> 00:27:38.174
Imagine if we sent it
to Mr. Boldwood.


375
00:27:40.090 --> 00:27:42.696
Ignoring you like that,
all high and mighty.


376
00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:44.934
Mr. Boldwood?

377
00:27:46.690 --> 00:27:48.260
Perhaps not?

378
00:27:48.690 --> 00:27:50.021
Why not?

379
00:27:50.170 --> 00:27:52.696
Because I don't think
he'll see the humor.


380
00:27:53.330 --> 00:27:54.377
(LAUGHING)
Perhaps he wouldn't,


381
00:27:54.450 --> 00:27:55.690
perhaps it's too much.

382
00:27:55.770 --> 00:27:57.898
Mr. Boldwood.

383
00:27:58.050 --> 00:28:00.178
You're right.
Perhaps it is.


384
00:28:01.370 --> 00:28:03.099
So we're gonna
toss for it.


385
00:28:03.210 --> 00:28:04.211
Liddy!

386
00:28:04.290 --> 00:28:05.621
Come on.

387
00:28:08.130 --> 00:28:09.859
Open, Joseph.

388
00:28:10.050 --> 00:28:11.734
No, Jan Coggan.

389
00:28:11.890 --> 00:28:15.895
Open, Jan Coggan.
Closed, Boldwood.


390
00:28:16.610 --> 00:28:17.691
(LIDDY YELPS)

391
00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:27.100
Sergeant Troy, 11:00.

392
00:29:27.290 --> 00:29:28.860
Yes, Sergeant Troy. And?

393
00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:31.177
Miss Fanny Robbin.

394
00:29:31.330 --> 00:29:33.492
Welcome. Step down the front.

395
00:29:33.570 --> 00:29:35.334
(CHOIR SINGING HYMN)

396
00:29:40.290 --> 00:29:41.860
(EXHALES SHAKILY)

397
00:30:06.450 --> 00:30:07.861
(WHISPERS)
Where is she?


398
00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:09.455
I don't know.

399
00:30:10.170 --> 00:30:11.615
(DOOR OPENS)

400
00:30:11.690 --> 00:30:13.135
FEMALE PARISHIONER: Here she comes.

401
00:30:18.450 --> 00:30:19.690
Oh.

402
00:30:29.130 --> 00:30:30.939
DOGGETT: (WHISPERS)
Sorry I'm late, old boy.


403
00:30:32.170 --> 00:30:33.501
Not long now.

404
00:30:49.730 --> 00:30:51.061
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

405
00:30:54.890 --> 00:30:58.258
Dearly beloved, we are
gathered here in the sight...


406
00:30:58.330 --> 00:30:59.331
(PEOPLE MURMURING)

407
00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:05.132
I can only wait
a few more minutes.


408
00:31:05.210 --> 00:31:06.575
She'll be here.

409
00:31:33.370 --> 00:31:35.213
(WHISPERS) What do you
think is happening?


410
00:31:36.010 --> 00:31:38.456
DOGGETT: I don't think
she's coming, old boy.


411
00:32:04.850 --> 00:32:06.852
(SHEEP BLEATING)

412
00:32:08.450 --> 00:32:11.101
Come on. Go on, off you go.
That's it. Go on.


413
00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:13.010
Morning, my love.

414
00:32:13.210 --> 00:32:14.450
Come on.

415
00:32:14.530 --> 00:32:16.419
(TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

416
00:32:17.610 --> 00:32:19.260
Bring them in, John.

417
00:32:24.610 --> 00:32:25.657
GABRIEL: Grab this one.

418
00:32:25.730 --> 00:32:27.016
Miss Everdene's here now,

419
00:32:27.090 --> 00:32:28.171
so you better do
your best work.


420
00:32:28.250 --> 00:32:29.695
I'm looking
at you, Coggan.


421
00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:31.255
COGGAN: Yeah,
you keep quiet, Liddy.


422
00:32:31.330 --> 00:32:32.331
(LAUGHING)

423
00:32:40.290 --> 00:32:41.337
What you doing?

424
00:32:44.170 --> 00:32:46.059
Perhaps you'd care
to lend a hand?


425
00:32:47.010 --> 00:32:48.455
You don't
think I would?


426
00:32:48.610 --> 00:32:49.975
No, you wouldn't.

427
00:32:51.370 --> 00:32:52.815
Come here.

428
00:32:57.170 --> 00:32:58.695
COGGAN: There,
she's getting in.


429
00:32:58.770 --> 00:33:00.295
(ALL CHEERING)

430
00:33:01.130 --> 00:33:02.655
Well done, ma'am.

431
00:33:25.090 --> 00:33:28.094
COGGAN: Gangway through.
Hey, Joseph. Joseph, look.


432
00:34:05.850 --> 00:34:08.057
Good morning,
Mr. Boldwood.


433
00:34:11.010 --> 00:34:12.250
Miss Everdene.

434
00:34:12.370 --> 00:34:16.375
Mr. Boldwood wondered if
he might have a word with you.


435
00:34:19.930 --> 00:34:23.173
Mr. Boldwood.
Of course.


436
00:34:24.290 --> 00:34:28.693
WILLIAM: One thousand acres.
A mix of arable and livestock.


437
00:34:29.370 --> 00:34:30.735
Adjacent to Everdene.

438
00:34:31.170 --> 00:34:34.572
An orchard. Glasshouse.

439
00:34:35.850 --> 00:34:37.818
I have some interesting pigs.
(LAUGHS)


440
00:34:40.370 --> 00:34:42.532
Some other time,
perhaps.


441
00:34:47.650 --> 00:34:48.981
Thank you.

442
00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:02.655
You have a very
beautiful house.


443
00:35:08.170 --> 00:35:09.456
Mr. Boldwood?

444
00:35:12.490 --> 00:35:13.901
Miss Everdene.

445
00:35:15.690 --> 00:35:17.215
I want

446
00:35:18.370 --> 00:35:21.374
very much,
more than anything,


447
00:35:22.450 --> 00:35:24.259
to have you as my wife.

448
00:35:25.050 --> 00:35:28.054
Miss Everdene,
marry me.


449
00:35:32.250 --> 00:35:33.251
(STAMMERING) I...

450
00:35:35.010 --> 00:35:37.012
I feel...

451
00:35:39.570 --> 00:35:42.733
Though I respect you
very much,


452
00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:48.418
I do not feel
what would justify me


453
00:35:52.050 --> 00:35:54.337
in accepting your offer.

454
00:35:58.370 --> 00:36:01.897
I have known
disappointments before,


455
00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:05.293
but I would never have
asked in this instance


456
00:36:05.370 --> 00:36:07.179
had I not been, er,

457
00:36:08.290 --> 00:36:10.054
led to believe...

458
00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:15.011
Unless...
Unless I am mistaken.


459
00:36:16.730 --> 00:36:18.300
BATHSHEBA: The valentine.

460
00:36:19.650 --> 00:36:20.731
No, you're not mistaken,

461
00:36:20.810 --> 00:36:22.938
but I should
never have sent it.


462
00:36:24.290 --> 00:36:27.100
Forgive me, it was thoughtless
to disturb your peace of mind.


463
00:36:27.170 --> 00:36:28.660
So you meant it as a joke?

464
00:36:28.730 --> 00:36:31.973
No. No, not as a joke.

465
00:36:33.530 --> 00:36:37.421
Not exactly.
It was impetuous.


466
00:36:37.530 --> 00:36:38.656
I see.

467
00:36:39.890 --> 00:36:41.938
Perhaps you think
I am too old?


468
00:36:42.170 --> 00:36:45.014
But I will care for you
more than anyone your own age.


469
00:36:45.490 --> 00:36:47.379
I'm sure you would...
I will protect you.


470
00:36:48.450 --> 00:36:50.896
You shall have dresses,

471
00:36:52.010 --> 00:36:55.173
a gig. Uh, a piano.

472
00:36:58.570 --> 00:36:59.856
I amuse you?

473
00:37:01.650 --> 00:37:03.015
No.

474
00:37:04.250 --> 00:37:05.695
It's only...

475
00:37:06.850 --> 00:37:08.852
I have a piano.

476
00:37:10.330 --> 00:37:12.776
And I have my own farm.

477
00:37:13.890 --> 00:37:15.540
And I have no need
for a husband,


478
00:37:16.530 --> 00:37:19.659
no matter how honored
I am by the offer.


479
00:37:25.090 --> 00:37:27.457
I think I'd like
to return home.


480
00:37:27.650 --> 00:37:30.574
Yes, er... I'll, er...

481
00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:33.617
I'll get someone to drive you.

482
00:37:34.170 --> 00:37:36.741
Mr. Boldwood,
I've made you miserable.


483
00:37:36.810 --> 00:37:38.414
It was very wicked of me.

484
00:37:38.490 --> 00:37:40.492
Will you reconsider?

485
00:37:43.290 --> 00:37:45.099
Let me think.

486
00:37:47.650 --> 00:37:48.856
Yes.

487
00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:51.978
Yes, I'll give you time.

488
00:37:53.170 --> 00:37:54.820
I will wait.

489
00:38:20.370 --> 00:38:21.895
You're working
late, Mr. Oak.


490
00:38:27.050 --> 00:38:28.973
Will you teach me?

491
00:38:30.210 --> 00:38:31.496
Here.

492
00:38:32.970 --> 00:38:34.495
Spin the wheel.

493
00:38:35.290 --> 00:38:37.292
Incline it, like that.

494
00:38:38.610 --> 00:38:40.772
And slide it gently.
Spin the wheel.


495
00:38:43.410 --> 00:38:46.892
Bit faster. Like that.
Very good.


496
00:38:48.410 --> 00:38:49.741
Now slide it.

497
00:38:49.890 --> 00:38:51.221
I... It's...

498
00:38:52.250 --> 00:38:54.651
Getting stuck.

499
00:39:01.610 --> 00:39:03.294
I wanted to ask,

500
00:39:03.890 --> 00:39:06.131
did the men say anything
today about Mr. Boldwood?


501
00:39:06.210 --> 00:39:07.336
They did.

502
00:39:07.490 --> 00:39:08.537
What did they say?

503
00:39:08.810 --> 00:39:11.814
That you'd be married
before the end of the year.


504
00:39:12.170 --> 00:39:13.660
Come on.

505
00:39:14.770 --> 00:39:15.817
(CHUCKLES)

506
00:39:15.890 --> 00:39:17.813
Well, I'd like you
to contradict it, to the men.


507
00:39:18.730 --> 00:39:20.255
Well, Bathsheba...

508
00:39:20.410 --> 00:39:21.980
"Miss Everdene," please.

509
00:39:24.730 --> 00:39:27.051
If Mr. Boldwood did really
speak of marriage,


510
00:39:27.170 --> 00:39:29.377
I'm not going to tell
stories just to please you.


511
00:39:31.010 --> 00:39:33.138
I just said I wanted you
to mention to the men


512
00:39:33.210 --> 00:39:35.451
that it might not be true
I was going to marry him.


513
00:39:35.570 --> 00:39:37.732
I could say that
if you wish.


514
00:39:37.810 --> 00:39:39.778
But I could also give you an
opinion on what you've done.


515
00:39:39.850 --> 00:39:42.774
I dare say, but I don't want
your opinion, Mr. Oak.


516
00:39:45.330 --> 00:39:47.458
I suppose not.

517
00:39:58.770 --> 00:40:00.772
Well, what is your opinion?

518
00:40:01.770 --> 00:40:03.534
That you're greatly to blame
for playing pranks


519
00:40:03.610 --> 00:40:05.772
on a man like Mr. Boldwood.

520
00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:09.458
Your actions were
unworthy of you.


521
00:40:09.770 --> 00:40:15.061
Unworthy? May I ask
where my unworthiness lies?


522
00:40:15.650 --> 00:40:17.652
In rejecting you, perhaps?

523
00:40:18.010 --> 00:40:19.535
I've long given up
thinking of that.


524
00:40:20.570 --> 00:40:22.334
Or wishing it, either.

525
00:40:24.970 --> 00:40:26.176
But I will say this.

526
00:40:26.250 --> 00:40:28.856
Leading on a man you
don't care for is beneath you.


527
00:40:31.730 --> 00:40:35.052
I cannot allow a man to
criticize my private conduct.


528
00:40:35.210 --> 00:40:37.330
You will please leave the farm
at the end of the week.


529
00:40:42.410 --> 00:40:43.821
(METAL CLANGS)

530
00:40:45.530 --> 00:40:47.532
I'd prefer to go at once.

531
00:40:47.890 --> 00:40:50.370
Then go. I never want to
see your face again.


532
00:40:52.410 --> 00:40:54.538
Very well, Miss Everdene.

533
00:41:00.930 --> 00:41:02.091
(DOOR SLAMS)

534
00:41:17.010 --> 00:41:18.660
(SHEEP BLEATING)

535
00:41:31.210 --> 00:41:34.054
Whoa, there we are.
There.


536
00:41:37.970 --> 00:41:39.415
What's wrong with them?

537
00:41:39.890 --> 00:41:41.574
They broke fence
and ate the young clover.


538
00:41:41.650 --> 00:41:42.856
Makes their stomachs swell.

539
00:41:43.050 --> 00:41:44.415
(BREATHING WEAKLY)

540
00:41:44.930 --> 00:41:46.091
BATHSHEBA: Well,
what do we do now?


541
00:41:46.170 --> 00:41:48.172
JOSEPH: Nothing.
The whole flock is blasted.


542
00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:49.940
You mean they're
all going to die?


543
00:41:50.010 --> 00:41:51.011
Most probably.

544
00:41:51.170 --> 00:41:52.171
Another one gone here, ma'am.

545
00:41:52.290 --> 00:41:54.418
Only one way
of saving them.


546
00:41:54.490 --> 00:41:57.255
You must pierce
their side with a tool.


547
00:41:57.610 --> 00:42:00.500
A hollow tube.
Pricker inside.


548
00:42:00.610 --> 00:42:02.374
Well, can you do it?

549
00:42:02.570 --> 00:42:03.776
This one's still alive.

550
00:42:03.930 --> 00:42:05.170
No.

551
00:42:05.290 --> 00:42:07.258
Can I?
Oh, good Lord, no.


552
00:42:07.770 --> 00:42:09.420
One inch to
the right or the left,


553
00:42:09.490 --> 00:42:11.492
and you kill
the ewe for sure.


554
00:42:11.610 --> 00:42:15.501
Not even a shepherd
can do it, as a rule.


555
00:42:16.130 --> 00:42:17.780
Well, who, then?

556
00:42:28.610 --> 00:42:29.691
(SIGHS)

557
00:42:33.610 --> 00:42:35.021
Gabriel!

558
00:42:36.610 --> 00:42:38.021
Gabriel!

559
00:42:38.130 --> 00:42:40.258
Gabriel Oak, wait!

560
00:42:41.770 --> 00:42:42.976
Miss Everdene needs you.

561
00:42:48.690 --> 00:42:52.331
Why are you alone?
Did you find him?


562
00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:54.095
Yes, miss.

563
00:42:55.050 --> 00:42:56.336
So what did he say?

564
00:42:58.250 --> 00:42:59.695
He said...

565
00:43:01.210 --> 00:43:02.541
BATHSHEBA: Joseph?

566
00:43:03.810 --> 00:43:04.891
He said you're
to go in person


567
00:43:04.970 --> 00:43:06.650
and request him civilly
in a proper manner.


568
00:43:08.250 --> 00:43:10.651
Where does he get his airs?
I'll do no such thing.


569
00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:13.815
He said you'd say that.

570
00:43:13.890 --> 00:43:17.258
He said to reply,
"Beggars can't be choosers."


571
00:43:20.570 --> 00:43:22.220
(HORSE APPROACHING)

572
00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:39.819
(PANTING) Mr. Oak.

573
00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:43.741
Gabriel.

574
00:43:45.650 --> 00:43:47.175
Gabriel.

575
00:43:49.330 --> 00:43:51.458
Please don't
desert me, Gabriel.


576
00:43:53.410 --> 00:43:54.900
I need your help.

577
00:44:15.130 --> 00:44:17.019
Make room for me.

578
00:44:45.890 --> 00:44:46.937
LIDDY: I wanna see.

579
00:44:47.010 --> 00:44:48.250
COGGAN: No, don't you start,
Liddy, be quiet.


580
00:44:48.370 --> 00:44:50.259
GABRIEL: Find the spot.

581
00:44:52.650 --> 00:44:54.175
Between the ribs.

582
00:44:56.890 --> 00:44:58.380
Oh, Lord!
No, no, no, no, no.


583
00:44:58.490 --> 00:45:00.174
Now...

584
00:45:00.650 --> 00:45:02.652
LIDDY: I can see
his heart beating.


585
00:45:03.130 --> 00:45:04.575
(AIR HISSING)

586
00:45:07.130 --> 00:45:08.330
Come on.
COGGAN: Come on, girl.


587
00:45:09.690 --> 00:45:10.816
GABRIEL: Come on.

588
00:45:10.890 --> 00:45:12.490
She'll be all right.
She'll be all right.


589
00:45:12.530 --> 00:45:13.941
You all right?
You all right, Pixie?


590
00:45:14.050 --> 00:45:15.540
Yeah, come on.
(BLEATING)


591
00:45:15.610 --> 00:45:16.816
All right, Pixie! Pixie!

592
00:45:16.970 --> 00:45:18.176
(LAUGHTER)

593
00:45:19.130 --> 00:45:20.734
Hey! Come here!

594
00:45:24.770 --> 00:45:26.613
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)
(BLEATING)


595
00:45:29.730 --> 00:45:31.494
(COGGAN WHISTLING)

596
00:45:50.930 --> 00:45:53.331
JOSEPH: <i>Lay me low</i>

597
00:45:54.170 --> 00:45:56.457
<i>Lay me low</i>

598
00:45:57.250 --> 00:46:01.380
<i>Where no-one can see me</i>

599
00:46:02.370 --> 00:46:05.533
<i>Where no-one can find me</i>

600
00:46:05.850 --> 00:46:10.936
<i>Where no-one can hurt me</i>

601
00:46:11.290 --> 00:46:12.780
(ALL CHEERING)

602
00:46:19.970 --> 00:46:20.971
Get out.

603
00:46:22.130 --> 00:46:23.973
Please, quiet.

604
00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:32.659
<i>Oh, early one morning
As I was a walking</i>


605
00:46:34.050 --> 00:46:40.057
<i>The fields and the meadows
They looked so green and gay</i>


606
00:46:40.650 --> 00:46:43.654
<i>The birds sang so sweetly</i>

607
00:46:43.810 --> 00:46:47.212
<i>So pleasant and so charming</i>

608
00:46:47.570 --> 00:46:49.891
<i>So early in the morning</i>

609
00:46:50.050 --> 00:46:51.176
<i>At the break of day</i>

610
00:46:51.250 --> 00:46:54.379
Miss. Mr. Boldwood is here.

611
00:46:54.490 --> 00:46:57.573
Thank you. Thank you, Jan.
Jan, thank you.


612
00:46:57.650 --> 00:46:59.857
(APPLAUDING AND CHEERING)

613
00:47:01.090 --> 00:47:02.580
Mr. Boldwood.

614
00:47:02.650 --> 00:47:05.256
What a pleasant surprise.
Will you join us?


615
00:47:05.330 --> 00:47:07.492
(ALL TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

616
00:47:21.570 --> 00:47:22.901
Nice to have you, sir.

617
00:47:26.690 --> 00:47:28.260
JACOB: A song, ma'am.

618
00:47:28.370 --> 00:47:30.293
I have no voice.

619
00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:31.496
(ALL PROTESTING)

620
00:47:31.570 --> 00:47:33.971
JACOB: Come on, ma'am,
you've got a lovely voice.


621
00:47:34.090 --> 00:47:36.252
(ALL CHEERING ENCOURAGINGLY)

622
00:47:46.050 --> 00:47:51.216
<i>Come all you fair
and tender girls</i>


623
00:47:51.810 --> 00:47:57.419
<i>That flourish in your prime</i>

624
00:47:57.770 --> 00:48:03.140
<i>Beware, beware
Keep your garden fair</i>


625
00:48:03.730 --> 00:48:09.134
<i>Let no man steal your thyme</i>

626
00:48:09.570 --> 00:48:14.736
<i>Let no man steal your thyme</i>

627
00:48:15.730 --> 00:48:20.736
<i>For when your thyme
it is past and gone</i>


628
00:48:21.730 --> 00:48:27.100
<i>He'll care no more for you</i>

629
00:48:27.930 --> 00:48:33.778
<i>And every place where
your thyme was waste</i>


630
00:48:33.850 --> 00:48:39.016
<i>Will all spread o'er with rue</i>

631
00:48:39.610 --> 00:48:44.491
<i>Will all spread o'er with rue</i>

632
00:48:46.130 --> 00:48:50.931
<i>The gardener's son
was standing by</i>


633
00:48:51.770 --> 00:48:56.014
<i>Three flowers he gave to me</i>

634
00:48:57.770 --> 00:49:03.061
<i>The pink, the blue
and the violet true</i>


635
00:49:03.690 --> 00:49:08.981
<i>And the red, red rosy tree</i>

636
00:49:09.610 --> 00:49:14.298
<i>And the red, red rosy tree</i>

637
00:49:15.650 --> 00:49:20.861
<i>But I refused
the red rose bush</i>


638
00:49:21.810 --> 00:49:26.816
<i>And gained the willow tree</i>

639
00:49:27.690 --> 00:49:32.981
<i>That all the world
may plainly see</i>


640
00:49:34.050 --> 00:49:38.851
<i>How my love slighted me</i>

641
00:49:39.970 --> 00:49:45.932
<i>How my love slighted me</i>

642
00:49:46.650 --> 00:49:49.096
(ALL APPLAUDING)

643
00:49:50.850 --> 00:49:53.012
I thought we were
rather good together.


644
00:49:53.090 --> 00:49:54.330
So did I.

645
00:49:54.490 --> 00:49:57.334
We would make
a fine duo.


646
00:49:57.490 --> 00:49:59.379
I wanted to thank you
for not approaching me


647
00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:01.333
on that subject again.

648
00:50:03.170 --> 00:50:05.696
Well, it has
not been easy.


649
00:50:14.170 --> 00:50:16.218
Do you wish me to, er,

650
00:50:16.290 --> 00:50:18.019
accompany you back
to the house?


651
00:50:19.210 --> 00:50:21.133
No, I like to walk around
the farm every night


652
00:50:21.210 --> 00:50:22.894
to make sure all is safe.

653
00:50:24.130 --> 00:50:27.373
Then I...
I can walk with you.


654
00:50:27.730 --> 00:50:29.732
I've done it
many times alone.


655
00:50:30.890 --> 00:50:32.380
Good night,
Mr. Boldwood.


656
00:50:32.450 --> 00:50:35.135
You've been very kind.
A pleasure to see you.


657
00:51:09.090 --> 00:51:10.421
(GASPS)

658
00:51:10.570 --> 00:51:12.174
Who are you?

659
00:51:12.330 --> 00:51:13.980
I'm sorry.
I seem to be lost.


660
00:51:14.450 --> 00:51:17.135
We're entangled.
Are you hurt?


661
00:51:17.450 --> 00:51:18.576
No.

662
00:51:18.770 --> 00:51:19.850
I'm looking
for Weatherbury.


663
00:51:19.930 --> 00:51:21.056
I hope I didn't
startle you.


664
00:51:21.130 --> 00:51:23.258
We've got hitched
together somehow.


665
00:51:23.330 --> 00:51:24.855
Here, allow me.

666
00:51:24.930 --> 00:51:27.410
No. No. Please,
let me do it myself.


667
00:51:29.170 --> 00:51:31.650
If you lift your
foot for a moment.


668
00:51:45.810 --> 00:51:47.335
Please don't stare.

669
00:51:47.450 --> 00:51:50.181
I don't think I've ever seen
a face as beautiful as yours.


670
00:51:50.610 --> 00:51:51.850
(FABRIC RIPS)

671
00:51:54.610 --> 00:51:58.456
You shouldn't be here.
Please let me have the lamp.


672
00:52:08.890 --> 00:52:12.019
FARMHAND: A mighty impressive
harvest this looks like.


673
00:52:15.970 --> 00:52:18.496
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

674
00:52:23.730 --> 00:52:24.811
LIDDY: Miss,

675
00:52:25.730 --> 00:52:27.220
look.

676
00:52:31.170 --> 00:52:32.660
Who is he, Liddy?

677
00:52:32.810 --> 00:52:35.017
Sergeant Francis Troy.

678
00:52:35.090 --> 00:52:38.219
Noble blood, full of promise.
Very sharp and trim.


679
00:52:39.490 --> 00:52:40.490
Well-educated.

680
00:52:40.530 --> 00:52:42.339
There was good things
expected of him.


681
00:52:42.850 --> 00:52:45.501
He threw it all in
to be a soldier.


682
00:52:47.090 --> 00:52:48.580
Well, I won't have it.

683
00:52:48.730 --> 00:52:50.220
What are you doing, miss?

684
00:52:50.330 --> 00:52:52.571
I'm going to
tell him to leave.


685
00:52:57.690 --> 00:52:58.976
Sergeant Troy,

686
00:52:59.050 --> 00:53:01.621
I must absolutely insist that
you leave at this very moment.


687
00:53:01.690 --> 00:53:03.215
I can't.

688
00:53:03.370 --> 00:53:05.213
Will you follow me, please?

689
00:53:07.130 --> 00:53:08.370
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

690
00:53:25.810 --> 00:53:27.380
What angers you, exactly?

691
00:53:28.530 --> 00:53:29.530
Please.

692
00:53:29.610 --> 00:53:31.578
What I said
or the way I said it?


693
00:53:31.730 --> 00:53:33.255
You must know.

694
00:53:33.770 --> 00:53:34.851
There must be some man

695
00:53:34.930 --> 00:53:36.330
who tells you
that you're beautiful.


696
00:53:36.570 --> 00:53:38.538
Oh, not to my face, not...

697
00:53:38.610 --> 00:53:40.374
But there is someone
who kisses you?


698
00:53:40.450 --> 00:53:41.611
I've never been kissed.

699
00:53:48.290 --> 00:53:51.453
Why couldn't you have just
passed by and said nothing?


700
00:53:53.010 --> 00:53:54.171
Do you forgive me?

701
00:53:56.570 --> 00:53:58.254
I do not.
Why?


702
00:53:58.410 --> 00:54:00.890
Because the things you say...

703
00:54:00.970 --> 00:54:02.859
I said that
you were beautiful.


704
00:54:07.770 --> 00:54:10.091
I wonder if you fight
as well as you speak.


705
00:54:10.170 --> 00:54:11.456
Better.

706
00:54:17.170 --> 00:54:20.697
Meet me. Tomorrow.

707
00:54:22.090 --> 00:54:23.819
I can't.

708
00:54:23.970 --> 00:54:25.176
You don't want to?

709
00:54:25.370 --> 00:54:26.610
Yes, but...

710
00:54:26.690 --> 00:54:28.101
Then you must.
I mustn't.


711
00:54:28.450 --> 00:54:30.179
(WHISPERS) Nobody would know.

712
00:54:32.850 --> 00:54:34.534
Please go now.

713
00:54:35.450 --> 00:54:36.781
Tomorrow.

714
00:54:37.450 --> 00:54:38.781
8:00.

715
00:54:40.010 --> 00:54:42.012
The hollow in the ferns.

716
00:54:51.290 --> 00:54:52.655
(SIGHS)

717
00:54:53.730 --> 00:54:55.334
(POCKET WATCH TICKING)

718
00:56:42.250 --> 00:56:43.251
Do you trust me?

719
00:56:44.930 --> 00:56:46.011
I do.

720
00:56:52.010 --> 00:56:53.774
I give you my word
as a soldier,


721
00:56:53.850 --> 00:56:55.659
I will not harm you.

722
00:56:55.770 --> 00:56:57.772
The sword is blunt,

723
00:56:58.250 --> 00:57:01.094
but you must not flinch.

724
00:57:01.690 --> 00:57:03.772
I'll try not to.

725
00:57:36.690 --> 00:57:37.851
(GRUNTS)

726
00:57:49.490 --> 00:57:51.379
You cut my hair.

727
00:57:54.050 --> 00:57:55.973
This sword could
skin you alive.


728
00:57:56.530 --> 00:57:58.976
But you told me I was safe.

729
00:57:59.170 --> 00:58:01.571
And you were.
Entirely safe.


730
00:58:02.210 --> 00:58:04.338
I gave you my word.

731
00:58:06.050 --> 00:58:08.178
Now I will take this.

732
00:58:17.050 --> 00:58:18.700
(BATHSHEBA MOANING)

733
00:59:26.130 --> 00:59:27.620
Miss Everdene.

734
00:59:29.090 --> 00:59:30.819
Perhaps I could
walk with you?


735
00:59:30.970 --> 00:59:33.450
I'm quite happy
to walk by myself.


736
00:59:35.410 --> 00:59:37.811
You should have nothing
to do with him.


737
00:59:38.130 --> 00:59:40.132
He's not good
enough for you.


738
00:59:40.610 --> 00:59:42.772
He's a perfectly decent man.

739
00:59:43.970 --> 00:59:45.256
That's not what I believe.

740
00:59:45.330 --> 00:59:47.936
Why? What have you heard?

741
00:59:49.290 --> 00:59:52.772
You don't know him at all.
It's all rumors.


742
00:59:53.170 --> 00:59:54.730
Prejudice simply because
he's a soldier.


743
00:59:54.770 --> 00:59:57.296
I like soldiers.
But not this one.


744
00:59:57.370 --> 00:59:59.771
I believe him to have
no conscience at all.


745
01:00:00.810 --> 01:00:03.211
Stay clear.
Don't listen to him.


746
01:00:03.290 --> 01:00:04.940
Don't believe him.

747
01:00:05.330 --> 01:00:06.616
Get rid of him.

748
01:00:07.050 --> 01:00:08.814
And what is it to you?

749
01:00:11.970 --> 01:00:13.540
I'm not such a fool
as to imagine


750
01:00:13.610 --> 01:00:16.580
I might stand a chance now
that you are so above me.


751
01:00:16.650 --> 01:00:20.496
But don't suppose I'm content
to stay a nobody all my life.


752
01:00:21.010 --> 01:00:23.661
One day I will leave you.
You can be sure of that.


753
01:00:24.170 --> 01:00:26.298
But for now,
I care for you too much


754
01:00:26.370 --> 01:00:28.737
to see you go to ruin
because of him.


755
01:00:30.690 --> 01:00:33.534
So if you don't mind, I'll...

756
01:00:35.490 --> 01:00:37.652
I'll stay by your side.

757
01:00:39.810 --> 01:00:41.812
Good evening.

758
01:00:59.650 --> 01:01:01.778
BATHSHEBA: <i>Mr. Boldwood,</i>

759
01:01:01.850 --> 01:01:04.820
<i>you have been a dear friend
to me these past months.</i>


760
01:01:04.890 --> 01:01:07.131
<i>And it is because
I value our friendship</i>


761
01:01:07.210 --> 01:01:09.690
<i>so greatly that I am writing.</i>

762
01:01:10.370 --> 01:01:13.374
<i>I am honored by your proposal</i>

763
01:01:13.530 --> 01:01:15.692
<i>and have given it
much thought,</i>


764
01:01:15.770 --> 01:01:18.137
<i>but I must tell you that,
to my own surprise,</i>


765
01:01:18.210 --> 01:01:20.451
<i>I have undergone
what can only be described</i>


766
01:01:20.530 --> 01:01:22.851
<i>as a change of heart</i>

767
01:01:22.930 --> 01:01:25.695
<i>And I'm afraid
I cannot accept your offer.</i>


768
01:01:48.930 --> 01:01:51.410
I wasn't sure you'd be here.

769
01:01:51.770 --> 01:01:53.932
Where else would I be?

770
01:01:56.410 --> 01:01:58.060
You ready?

771
01:02:00.570 --> 01:02:02.413
Are you sure?

772
01:02:06.730 --> 01:02:08.892
How does this sound?

773
01:02:09.970 --> 01:02:12.735
Mrs. Bathsheba Troy.

774
01:02:12.810 --> 01:02:15.017
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING)

775
01:02:28.450 --> 01:02:29.815
(WHISPERS) All right?

776
01:03:26.130 --> 01:03:27.814
Walk on.

777
01:04:06.410 --> 01:04:08.174
(WIND HOWLING)

778
01:04:09.250 --> 01:04:10.297
(BARN DOOR SLAMS)

779
01:04:21.570 --> 01:04:22.981
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

780
01:04:29.690 --> 01:04:32.011
(BAND PLAYING UPBEAT FOLK MUSIC)

781
01:05:00.130 --> 01:05:01.655
(LAUGHING)

782
01:05:09.530 --> 01:05:11.055
(some ENDS)

783
01:05:11.130 --> 01:05:12.859
(ALL APPLAUDING AND CHEERING)

784
01:05:15.530 --> 01:05:18.659
FRANCIS: Gentlemen.
Ladies and gentlemen.


785
01:05:20.290 --> 01:05:24.693
A short time ago,
I had the privilege


786
01:05:25.650 --> 01:05:30.577
and the simple fortune
of meeting this angel.


787
01:05:31.450 --> 01:05:32.895
Your mistress.

788
01:05:33.730 --> 01:05:36.893
And now I stand before
you her husband,


789
01:05:37.930 --> 01:05:39.295
your master,

790
01:05:40.490 --> 01:05:43.221
and the proudest man
you will ever see.


791
01:05:43.650 --> 01:05:47.735
So, please,
charge your glasses


792
01:05:47.810 --> 01:05:52.771
and sing out to
my most beautiful wife,


793
01:05:53.370 --> 01:05:57.091
Mrs. Bathsheba Troy.

794
01:05:57.770 --> 01:06:00.614
(ALL CHEERING)

795
01:06:02.970 --> 01:06:06.179
Miss Everdene,
there's going to be a storm.


796
01:06:06.290 --> 01:06:10.090
Oak, you big lump.
To me.


797
01:06:10.170 --> 01:06:12.093
There's going to be a storm.

798
01:06:12.170 --> 01:06:15.379
We need to protect the ricks
or we'll lose the harvest.


799
01:06:16.010 --> 01:06:18.377
I need five to six men
for an hour, no more.


800
01:06:18.490 --> 01:06:20.174
Frank, perhaps we ought to...
No.


801
01:06:20.250 --> 01:06:21.854
Darling, it's our
wedding celebration.


802
01:06:23.050 --> 01:06:27.339
It will not rain tonight.
My wife forbids it.


803
01:06:28.050 --> 01:06:30.018
Now if you'll excuse me.

804
01:06:31.010 --> 01:06:32.853
Friends!

805
01:06:33.690 --> 01:06:34.691
One more thing.

806
01:06:36.090 --> 01:06:40.698
I may no longer
be Sergeant Troy,


807
01:06:40.810 --> 01:06:44.781
but I remain a soldier
in this one respect!


808
01:06:44.850 --> 01:06:45.931
(ALL CHEERING)

809
01:06:46.010 --> 01:06:49.696
The finest bottles
of French brandy,


810
01:06:50.690 --> 01:06:53.853
a triple-strength dose
for every man.


811
01:06:53.970 --> 01:06:55.131
Cheers! To your health!

812
01:06:55.330 --> 01:06:56.491
(ALL CHEERING)

813
01:06:56.570 --> 01:06:58.140
(MUSIC RESUMES)

814
01:07:01.290 --> 01:07:02.621
(INAUDIBLE)

815
01:07:08.650 --> 01:07:10.140
(WIND HOWLING)

816
01:07:24.210 --> 01:07:25.621
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

817
01:07:30.650 --> 01:07:32.379
(ALL CHEERING)

818
01:07:35.850 --> 01:07:40.697
<i>"Pretty Polly, Pretty Polly
It's I've come a-wooin"'</i>


819
01:07:41.290 --> 01:07:46.421
<i>"Pretty Polly, Pretty Polly
It's I've come a-wooin"'</i>


820
01:07:47.730 --> 01:07:50.415
<i>She says, "Creep and crawl
through the window, then</i>


821
01:07:50.610 --> 01:07:52.374
<i>"And let's get doin'</i>

822
01:07:52.450 --> 01:07:57.012
<i>"And lay your leg over me
Over me, do</i>


823
01:07:57.650 --> 01:08:02.650
<i>"Oh, me britches is tight
and I cannot undo 'em</i>


824
01:08:08.290 --> 01:08:10.531
<i>"There's a knife
on the windowsill</i>


825
01:08:10.610 --> 01:08:12.100
<i>"Love, take it to 'em</i>

826
01:08:12.690 --> 01:08:15.341
<i>"And lay your leg over me..."</i>

827
01:08:15.610 --> 01:08:17.419
(WIND HOWLING)
(GABRIEL PANTING)


828
01:08:34.650 --> 01:08:39.372
<i>About 40 weeks after,
the fine baby come bawlin'</i>


829
01:08:40.490 --> 01:08:44.973
<i>Never regretted
that creepin' and crawlin'</i>


830
01:08:45.050 --> 01:08:48.179
<i>"Lay your leg over me
Over me..."</i>


831
01:08:48.330 --> 01:08:49.661
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

832
01:09:19.490 --> 01:09:21.299
(RUMBLING CONTINUES)

833
01:09:36.130 --> 01:09:37.541
BATHSHEBA: Gabriel!

834
01:09:40.170 --> 01:09:41.171
Gabriel!

835
01:09:43.450 --> 01:09:44.611
What can I do?

836
01:09:44.730 --> 01:09:46.619
It's too dangerous!

837
01:09:46.690 --> 01:09:48.260
I'm coming up!

838
01:09:58.490 --> 01:09:59.616
Hold it down.

839
01:10:00.890 --> 01:10:02.779
Still no rain.

840
01:10:03.170 --> 01:10:04.899
It'll come.

841
01:10:16.330 --> 01:10:17.411
(THUNDER CRASHES)

842
01:10:17.570 --> 01:10:18.617
(YELPS)

843
01:10:18.690 --> 01:10:22.820
Come on, hold me!
Come here. Come here.


844
01:10:22.930 --> 01:10:24.659
(BOTH PANTING)

845
01:10:28.490 --> 01:10:30.572
Come here. Come on.

846
01:10:30.850 --> 01:10:32.420
(BOTH LAUGHING)

847
01:10:51.250 --> 01:10:53.332
Gabriel, I've been a fool.

848
01:10:54.010 --> 01:10:57.537
I've always had contempt
for silly girls


849
01:10:57.650 --> 01:11:00.938
dazzled by flattery
in a scarlet uniform and...


850
01:11:01.250 --> 01:11:04.140
And now I've done
what I swore I would never do.


851
01:11:06.410 --> 01:11:08.811
But he told me
about another woman,


852
01:11:09.610 --> 01:11:11.977
a woman more beautiful
that he'd loved before,


853
01:11:12.090 --> 01:11:13.933
and I couldn't bear it.

854
01:11:15.850 --> 01:11:17.693
So somewhere between
jealousy and distraction,


855
01:11:17.770 --> 01:11:18.931
I married him.

856
01:11:19.450 --> 01:11:22.340
I don't want an opinion
on the subject, I just...


857
01:11:22.890 --> 01:11:24.813
In fact, I forbid it.

858
01:11:30.210 --> 01:11:31.541
Go to bed.

859
01:11:32.810 --> 01:11:35.177
I'll finish it
on my own.


860
01:11:36.170 --> 01:11:37.854
Gabriel...

861
01:11:41.450 --> 01:11:43.054
Thank you.

862
01:12:08.210 --> 01:12:09.336
GABRIEL: Sir?

863
01:12:13.690 --> 01:12:14.896
Mr. Boldwood, sir!

864
01:12:15.770 --> 01:12:18.819
I wanted to ensure your
mistress' crops were safe.


865
01:12:19.130 --> 01:12:21.895
Good work, Gabriel.
She's lucky to have you.


866
01:12:23.130 --> 01:12:24.859
Wait a moment, sir.

867
01:12:32.930 --> 01:12:34.261
You seem unwell, sir.

868
01:12:35.130 --> 01:12:36.700
You should go home.

869
01:12:38.610 --> 01:12:39.611
Yes.

870
01:12:42.570 --> 01:12:44.538
Yes, I will.

871
01:12:49.850 --> 01:12:51.181
Oak.

872
01:12:53.170 --> 01:12:56.379
You know that things have
not gone well with me, lately.


873
01:12:57.970 --> 01:13:01.975
I was going to get a little
settled in life. But, er...


874
01:13:06.010 --> 01:13:08.012
It was not to be.

875
01:13:09.130 --> 01:13:10.495
(CHUCKLES)

876
01:13:10.970 --> 01:13:13.291
I daresay
I'm something of a...


877
01:13:14.090 --> 01:13:16.297
A joke about the parish.

878
01:13:17.170 --> 01:13:20.652
But I do wanna make
one thing clear.


879
01:13:21.210 --> 01:13:24.214
There was no jilting
on her part.


880
01:13:25.250 --> 01:13:29.938
We were never engaged.
No matter what people say.


881
01:13:31.570 --> 01:13:33.413
She promised me nothing.

882
01:13:39.050 --> 01:13:40.939
And yet,

883
01:13:41.570 --> 01:13:43.015
Gabriel,

884
01:13:46.130 --> 01:13:49.816
I feel the most
terrible grief.


885
01:13:56.450 --> 01:13:58.578
Not a word to her.

886
01:13:59.690 --> 01:14:02.296
We understand
each other, yes?


887
01:14:04.410 --> 01:14:05.411
Yes, sir.

888
01:14:56.410 --> 01:14:57.411
(CROWD GROANING)

889
01:14:57.570 --> 01:14:58.617
Damn and bother!

890
01:15:02.050 --> 01:15:03.575
Sit.

891
01:15:03.810 --> 01:15:06.097
Stay. Now, turn around.

892
01:15:12.250 --> 01:15:13.490
Can you spare
a coin, please?


893
01:15:13.650 --> 01:15:14.856
No, no.

894
01:15:15.570 --> 01:15:17.095
(BOTH GRUNTING)

895
01:15:17.210 --> 01:15:18.416
(CROWD SHOUTING)

896
01:15:18.970 --> 01:15:20.335
FRANCIS: Hit him!

897
01:15:20.850 --> 01:15:21.851
Come on!

898
01:15:23.370 --> 01:15:24.940
WOMAN: Knock him out!

899
01:15:26.290 --> 01:15:27.860
MAN: Hit him!

900
01:15:29.130 --> 01:15:30.575
(ALL CHEERING)

901
01:15:32.570 --> 01:15:34.971
Pay up.
Pay up, Mr. Troy.


902
01:15:35.810 --> 01:15:37.460
Just take it.

903
01:15:43.170 --> 01:15:44.251
FANNY: Sir, excuse me.

904
01:15:44.330 --> 01:15:45.980
Could you spare
a coin, please?


905
01:15:46.450 --> 01:15:47.895
No.

906
01:15:50.490 --> 01:15:51.651
Fanny?

907
01:15:59.530 --> 01:16:00.816
Hello, Frank.

908
01:16:03.170 --> 01:16:04.501
Hello.

909
01:16:06.890 --> 01:16:08.221
You're so pale.

910
01:16:08.850 --> 01:16:10.181
Oh, Frank.

911
01:16:10.250 --> 01:16:12.378
Darling,
your hands are shaking.


912
01:16:12.930 --> 01:16:15.900
I thought you said
All Souls, not All Saints.


913
01:16:15.970 --> 01:16:17.972
I went to the wrong church.

914
01:16:19.090 --> 01:16:23.061
When I got there, you'd gone.
And I don't blame you,


915
01:16:23.130 --> 01:16:25.531
but it's been very hard,
Frank. I...


916
01:16:25.650 --> 01:16:26.936
Not now.

917
01:16:28.130 --> 01:16:30.417
My wife mustn't see you.

918
01:16:31.050 --> 01:16:32.495
Your wife?

919
01:16:40.930 --> 01:16:42.295
(GASPS)

920
01:16:43.250 --> 01:16:45.571
Mrs. Troy is very beautiful.

921
01:16:47.330 --> 01:16:49.014
No more than you.

922
01:16:49.090 --> 01:16:50.330
(FANNY SOBBING)

923
01:16:51.610 --> 01:16:56.138
Frank, I must tell you,
I'm carrying your child.


924
01:16:56.330 --> 01:16:57.695
What?

925
01:17:09.970 --> 01:17:13.053
What if I told you that
I'd made a terrible mistake,


926
01:17:14.610 --> 01:17:16.851
but that I will make amends?

927
01:17:17.890 --> 01:17:19.221
I swear on my life

928
01:17:19.330 --> 01:17:22.174
I will find a home
for you and our baby.


929
01:17:22.610 --> 01:17:24.499
You've sworn before, Frank.

930
01:17:24.650 --> 01:17:26.493
No, this time... This time...

931
01:17:34.130 --> 01:17:36.736
Go to Budmouth.
Stay at the Union.


932
01:17:36.810 --> 01:17:38.699
The workhouse, Frank?

933
01:17:38.770 --> 01:17:40.613
Tonight, just tonight.
One night.


934
01:17:40.690 --> 01:17:43.534
And then meet me tomorrow
at 10:00 on the bridge.


935
01:17:44.010 --> 01:17:46.058
I'll bring you
all the money I have


936
01:17:46.130 --> 01:17:47.541
and I'll find
a home for you.


937
01:17:47.850 --> 01:17:49.739
You'll be safe, my darling.

938
01:17:49.810 --> 01:17:53.212
And I promise you,
I promise you


939
01:17:53.330 --> 01:17:55.378
I will make amends.

940
01:18:00.690 --> 01:18:02.419
Get back in the carriage.

941
01:18:02.730 --> 01:18:04.619
Do you know
who that woman is?


942
01:18:04.930 --> 01:18:06.091
I do.

943
01:18:06.370 --> 01:18:07.531
Who is she?

944
01:18:07.690 --> 01:18:08.816
She's nothing.

945
01:18:10.010 --> 01:18:12.092
Get back in the carriage.

946
01:18:13.050 --> 01:18:14.381
Frank...

947
01:18:43.970 --> 01:18:46.371
(PANTING)

948
01:19:12.810 --> 01:19:14.016
(GROANING)

949
01:19:23.610 --> 01:19:26.261
Could you let me
have £20?


950
01:19:28.810 --> 01:19:30.335
What for?

951
01:19:31.010 --> 01:19:32.580
I need it.

952
01:19:34.770 --> 01:19:37.694
If you continue to gamble,
we will lose the farm.


953
01:19:37.810 --> 01:19:38.891
It's not for gambling.

954
01:19:39.090 --> 01:19:40.171
What's it for?

955
01:19:40.290 --> 01:19:41.371
Why should it matter
what it's for?


956
01:19:41.450 --> 01:19:42.781
It's my money.

957
01:19:43.250 --> 01:19:45.378
I work for it,
don't I?


958
01:19:45.450 --> 01:19:48.056
No. You don't.

959
01:19:48.810 --> 01:19:50.972
Not proper farm work.

960
01:19:52.850 --> 01:19:55.251
Don't do something
you'll regret.


961
01:19:57.570 --> 01:20:01.177
The money is required
for farm expenses.


962
01:20:19.730 --> 01:20:21.459
(HORSE APPROACHING)

963
01:20:48.090 --> 01:20:49.694
UNDERTAKER: No mistake, Mr. Oak.

964
01:20:49.770 --> 01:20:52.455
This was Miss Robbin's
last known abode.


965
01:20:52.530 --> 01:20:53.691
BATHSHEBA: Fanny was
my uncle's servant


966
01:20:53.770 --> 01:20:55.499
and we shall treat
her with respect.


967
01:20:56.450 --> 01:20:58.532
Perhaps we should
take her to the church,


968
01:20:58.610 --> 01:21:00.135
just for tonight.

969
01:21:00.210 --> 01:21:02.531
No, bring her inside, please.

970
01:21:23.090 --> 01:21:24.854
What did she die of, Liddy?

971
01:21:26.610 --> 01:21:28.339
I don't know, miss.

972
01:21:30.530 --> 01:21:32.180
There were rumors, but...

973
01:21:33.010 --> 01:21:35.661
Fanny had a sweetheart,
didn't she?


974
01:21:36.170 --> 01:21:37.740
Yes, miss.

975
01:21:39.090 --> 01:21:41.013
A soldier.

976
01:21:45.010 --> 01:21:47.854
LIDDY: Please, come
and sit upstairs with me.


977
01:22:04.930 --> 01:22:08.093
I seem to cry
a great deal these days.


978
01:22:10.690 --> 01:22:12.215
I never used to cry at all.

979
01:22:22.810 --> 01:22:23.811
Good night, Liddy.

980
01:22:24.850 --> 01:22:26.739
'Night, miss.

981
01:22:36.450 --> 01:22:37.781
(DOOR CLOSES)

982
01:23:14.890 --> 01:23:16.096
(GASPS)

983
01:23:22.730 --> 01:23:24.141
What?

984
01:23:24.730 --> 01:23:25.856
Who is it?

985
01:23:25.930 --> 01:23:27.341
I can't say...

986
01:23:27.530 --> 01:23:28.975
Stay, stay. Stay.

987
01:23:49.010 --> 01:23:51.012
Don't kiss them, Frank.

988
01:23:51.330 --> 01:23:53.731
I'm still your wife.

989
01:24:01.410 --> 01:24:04.220
This woman,
dead as she is,


990
01:24:04.290 --> 01:24:10.218
is more to me than you
ever were, or are, or can be.


991
01:24:12.730 --> 01:24:14.812
You are nothing to me now.

992
01:24:17.210 --> 01:24:19.019
Nothing.

993
01:26:06.690 --> 01:26:09.057
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

994
01:26:26.610 --> 01:26:28.612
CONSTABLE: Mrs. Troy?

995
01:26:32.130 --> 01:26:34.178
I'm afraid...

996
01:26:34.250 --> 01:26:36.651
I'm afraid your
husband has drowned.


997
01:27:59.050 --> 01:28:00.575
(EXHALING)

998
01:28:10.690 --> 01:28:11.771
GABRIEL: That's a great
responsibility, sir.


999
01:28:11.850 --> 01:28:12.851
Nonsense.

1000
01:28:12.930 --> 01:28:14.290
No reason why a man
of your ability


1001
01:28:14.330 --> 01:28:16.901
shouldn't be able to
superintend two farms.


1002
01:28:17.010 --> 01:28:18.216
And why shouldn't there
be stronger links


1003
01:28:18.290 --> 01:28:19.940
between our establishments?

1004
01:28:20.010 --> 01:28:23.731
Think of it. Two thousand
acres under your sole charge.


1005
01:28:23.930 --> 01:28:25.819
A share of my profits.

1006
01:28:25.930 --> 01:28:27.050
Miss Everdene needs me here.

1007
01:28:27.090 --> 01:28:28.535
And her farm
will have priority.


1008
01:28:28.610 --> 01:28:29.975
I'd still need
Miss Everdene's permission.


1009
01:28:30.050 --> 01:28:31.131
But, of course.

1010
01:28:31.250 --> 01:28:32.411
Of course, I wouldn't
dare do anything


1011
01:28:32.490 --> 01:28:34.219
without her blessing. And,

1012
01:28:34.330 --> 01:28:36.856
if it'll help
sway your decision,


1013
01:28:41.130 --> 01:28:43.610
there's an old comrade
of yours here.


1014
01:28:45.570 --> 01:28:46.571
GABRIEL: Georgie!

1015
01:28:46.730 --> 01:28:47.936
Had to go all the way
to Norcombe Hill


1016
01:28:48.010 --> 01:28:49.057
to find this old fella.

1017
01:28:49.290 --> 01:28:50.371
You pleased?

1018
01:28:50.770 --> 01:28:52.420
Yes, sir, very much.

1019
01:28:52.530 --> 01:28:55.374
And I'll have your
decision soon, yes?


1020
01:28:55.850 --> 01:28:57.340
You will, sir.

1021
01:28:57.610 --> 01:28:59.374
Hey, Georgie.

1022
01:29:01.490 --> 01:29:02.491
Come on. Come on.

1023
01:29:02.610 --> 01:29:03.611
(BARKING PLAYFULLY)

1024
01:29:13.810 --> 01:29:15.300
Come on! Come on!

1025
01:29:17.130 --> 01:29:19.576
BATHSHEBA: Gabriel, you're
getting on in the world.


1026
01:29:20.170 --> 01:29:22.298
Of course you must
accept the offer.


1027
01:29:22.370 --> 01:29:24.498
GABRIEL: Only with
your approval.


1028
01:29:24.810 --> 01:29:26.619
If I lose the farm,
there may be no future


1029
01:29:26.690 --> 01:29:28.738
for any of us here.

1030
01:29:29.210 --> 01:29:31.417
You know where
my loyalty lies.


1031
01:29:33.970 --> 01:29:36.018
You're a man of great talent.

1032
01:29:36.330 --> 01:29:37.695
It's only natural
that you should rise.


1033
01:29:37.770 --> 01:29:39.977
I've no desire
to hold you back.


1034
01:29:42.610 --> 01:29:44.100
(HORSE NEIGHING)

1035
01:29:51.050 --> 01:29:52.176
Thank you.

1036
01:29:57.570 --> 01:29:59.652
Come on, Georgie.
Come on.


1037
01:30:03.730 --> 01:30:08.975
WILLIAM: Forgive me.
I understand there are debts.


1038
01:30:10.370 --> 01:30:12.020
Your late husband.

1039
01:30:13.170 --> 01:30:15.901
Perhaps... Perhaps we should
change the subject.


1040
01:30:15.970 --> 01:30:17.654
Perhaps I can help.

1041
01:30:22.090 --> 01:30:24.900
Mr. Boldwood,
that's a very kind offer,


1042
01:30:24.970 --> 01:30:27.541
but I would never dream
of accepting any money.


1043
01:30:31.890 --> 01:30:34.131
I am a middle-aged man

1044
01:30:35.690 --> 01:30:38.978
willing to protect you
for the rest of your life.


1045
01:30:41.330 --> 01:30:45.176
You may run your farm,
if you wish. Without risk.


1046
01:30:47.410 --> 01:30:49.014
I'll pay your

1047
01:30:50.090 --> 01:30:52.172
departed husband's debts

1048
01:30:52.250 --> 01:30:54.412
and guarantee
its financial stability.


1049
01:30:55.810 --> 01:30:58.017
It can be your pastime.

1050
01:31:00.250 --> 01:31:02.935
Of course, we'd need to wait,

1051
01:31:03.410 --> 01:31:05.492
for propriety's sake.

1052
01:31:06.170 --> 01:31:07.934
But when you're ready,

1053
01:31:08.770 --> 01:31:10.852
I'm offering you shelter.

1054
01:31:11.890 --> 01:31:15.895
Comfort. A safe harbor.

1055
01:31:18.970 --> 01:31:20.734
As my wife.

1056
01:31:25.290 --> 01:31:27.531
You must at least admire
my persistence.


1057
01:31:27.610 --> 01:31:29.021
(LAUGHS)

1058
01:31:30.730 --> 01:31:31.970
I do.

1059
01:31:32.050 --> 01:31:33.051
And like me?

1060
01:31:33.130 --> 01:31:34.177
Yes.

1061
01:31:35.370 --> 01:31:37.816
And respect me?

1062
01:31:37.890 --> 01:31:39.858
Yes. Very much.

1063
01:31:39.930 --> 01:31:42.217
Which is it?
Like or respect?


1064
01:31:45.810 --> 01:31:48.893
It is difficult for a woman
to define her feelings


1065
01:31:48.970 --> 01:31:51.621
in a language chiefly
made by men to express theirs.


1066
01:31:51.730 --> 01:31:54.574
If you worry about a lack
of passion on your part,


1067
01:31:54.650 --> 01:31:56.220
a lack of, er,

1068
01:31:58.850 --> 01:32:00.375
desire,

1069
01:32:01.330 --> 01:32:03.901
if you worry about marrying me

1070
01:32:03.970 --> 01:32:06.894
merely out of guilt,

1071
01:32:07.250 --> 01:32:08.820
and, er,

1072
01:32:09.810 --> 01:32:14.020
pity and compromise, well...

1073
01:32:15.250 --> 01:32:16.900
I don't mind.

1074
01:32:21.090 --> 01:32:22.854
GABRIEL: When must you
give your answer?


1075
01:32:22.970 --> 01:32:24.540
By Christmas.

1076
01:32:26.370 --> 01:32:28.213
It's a terrible responsibility.

1077
01:32:30.850 --> 01:32:33.296
I hold that man's
future in my hands.


1078
01:32:33.930 --> 01:32:36.058
His sanity, too, perhaps.

1079
01:32:36.130 --> 01:32:37.461
Could you care for him?

1080
01:32:37.530 --> 01:32:39.851
BATHSHEBA: You may suppose
love is wanting.


1081
01:32:41.730 --> 01:32:44.779
But love's a worn-out,
miserable thing for me now.


1082
01:32:44.850 --> 01:32:46.898
GABRIEL: Why are you
asking me?


1083
01:32:51.330 --> 01:32:53.981
I need someone
who's objective.


1084
01:32:54.050 --> 01:32:55.620
Indifferent.
(GABRIEL CHUCKLES)


1085
01:32:57.130 --> 01:32:59.940
Then I'm afraid you're
asking the wrong man.


1086
01:33:18.290 --> 01:33:19.860
Good evening, Mr. Oak.

1087
01:33:21.570 --> 01:33:23.015
GABRIEL: Good evening.

1088
01:33:41.410 --> 01:33:42.491
WORKMAN #1: That's it.

1089
01:33:42.650 --> 01:33:43.731
WORKMAN #2: Mind.

1090
01:33:50.730 --> 01:33:53.700
(ORGAN PLAYING)

1091
01:33:53.970 --> 01:33:59.500
<i>Rejoice</i>

1092
01:33:59.570 --> 01:34:03.575
<i>Emmanuel</i>

1093
01:34:03.650 --> 01:34:06.460
<i>Shall come to thee</i>

1094
01:34:06.530 --> 01:34:11.457
<i>O Israel</i>

1095
01:34:14.570 --> 01:34:18.575
<i>O come, Thou Rod of Jesse...</i>

1096
01:34:19.330 --> 01:34:21.697
WILLIAM: I appreciate you
coming along, Oak.


1097
01:34:21.810 --> 01:34:22.811
Ah!

1098
01:34:22.970 --> 01:34:25.257
Yes, very good.
Well done. Erm...


1099
01:34:25.330 --> 01:34:26.377
Just more... More things.

1100
01:34:26.530 --> 01:34:27.531
Yes, sir.

1101
01:34:30.690 --> 01:34:31.737
(SIGHS)

1102
01:34:31.810 --> 01:34:34.939
So what do you think?

1103
01:34:35.570 --> 01:34:38.221
I'm not in the habit of
organizing parties.


1104
01:34:38.490 --> 01:34:40.936
Perhaps we should make it
an annual event.


1105
01:34:41.010 --> 01:34:42.136
Every Christmas Eve.

1106
01:34:42.690 --> 01:34:44.260
I've invited
the whole village.


1107
01:34:44.330 --> 01:34:45.411
Do you think they'll come?

1108
01:34:45.490 --> 01:34:47.492
Do you think
Miss Everdene will come?


1109
01:34:47.570 --> 01:34:49.140
I'm sure she will.

1110
01:34:50.410 --> 01:34:51.411
Yes.

1111
01:34:52.170 --> 01:34:54.172
And you'll come
too, I hope.


1112
01:34:55.290 --> 01:34:57.861
I know Miss Everdene
would like you to be here.


1113
01:34:57.970 --> 01:34:59.381
Perhaps, for
an hour or so.


1114
01:35:01.450 --> 01:35:03.054
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

1115
01:35:04.370 --> 01:35:07.897
Look, I'm shaking.
I'm so nervous.


1116
01:35:08.890 --> 01:35:11.018
Gabriel, will you...

1117
01:35:11.370 --> 01:35:12.701
As well as you can, please.

1118
01:35:12.850 --> 01:35:14.181
I'll try.

1119
01:35:14.250 --> 01:35:17.254
Is there a knot that's
particularly fashionable?


1120
01:35:17.330 --> 01:35:18.491
(GABRIEL LAUGHING)

1121
01:35:19.250 --> 01:35:21.412
You're asking the wrong man.

1122
01:35:22.970 --> 01:35:24.415
What about women?

1123
01:35:25.330 --> 01:35:27.492
Does a woman keep her promise?

1124
01:35:28.730 --> 01:35:30.380
She has promised?

1125
01:35:31.130 --> 01:35:33.132
An implied promise.

1126
01:35:34.970 --> 01:35:36.381
Once again, I'm...

1127
01:35:36.530 --> 01:35:37.895
Will she do what's right?

1128
01:35:40.570 --> 01:35:42.493
If it's not
inconvenient to her.


1129
01:35:43.530 --> 01:35:45.851
Oak, you've become
quite cynical lately.


1130
01:35:46.850 --> 01:35:48.579
She never promised
that first time.


1131
01:35:48.690 --> 01:35:52.058
Therefore, she has
never broken her promise.


1132
01:35:52.530 --> 01:35:54.897
She hasn't promised
this time, either.


1133
01:35:55.850 --> 01:35:59.172
But she will. Tonight.

1134
01:35:59.690 --> 01:36:01.180
I know she will.

1135
01:36:03.130 --> 01:36:04.655
And when she does...

1136
01:36:10.490 --> 01:36:14.256
I wanted to tell you
in advance, Gabriel,


1137
01:36:15.770 --> 01:36:18.774
because I... I believe
I know your secret.


1138
01:36:21.970 --> 01:36:24.541
I've seen you together.

1139
01:36:26.010 --> 01:36:28.092
The way you speak to her.

1140
01:36:29.210 --> 01:36:30.814
And watch her.

1141
01:36:32.370 --> 01:36:34.498
And look after her.

1142
01:36:34.850 --> 01:36:37.137
And I know her, er,

1143
01:36:38.610 --> 01:36:42.092
profound affection for you.

1144
01:36:42.690 --> 01:36:44.931
You've behaved like a man,

1145
01:36:45.770 --> 01:36:47.181
and as the successful rival,

1146
01:36:47.290 --> 01:36:50.373
successful through
your kindness,


1147
01:36:50.450 --> 01:36:51.451
I wish to tell you

1148
01:36:53.890 --> 01:36:56.257
I am profoundly grateful.

1149
01:36:59.170 --> 01:37:00.581
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)
(BUTLER CLEARS THROAT)


1150
01:37:00.650 --> 01:37:03.256
The cook would like
a word, sir.


1151
01:37:30.450 --> 01:37:32.532
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

1152
01:37:32.610 --> 01:37:35.216
(LIVELY CHRISTMAS MUSIC PLAYING)

1153
01:38:11.490 --> 01:38:13.458
LIDDY: Kiss me. Joseph.

1154
01:38:13.530 --> 01:38:15.532
JOSEPH: No, please don't.
Liddy, don't.


1155
01:38:22.890 --> 01:38:24.779
(INDISTINCT)

1156
01:38:39.050 --> 01:38:40.814
GABRIEL: Would you excuse me?

1157
01:38:46.690 --> 01:38:48.499
I've come to say good night.

1158
01:38:48.610 --> 01:38:50.772
Go back and talk to
the poor things.


1159
01:38:50.850 --> 01:38:52.932
You've broken their hearts.

1160
01:38:53.570 --> 01:38:55.857
I don't suit
this kind of affair.


1161
01:38:56.890 --> 01:38:59.177
No. Nor do I.

1162
01:39:00.170 --> 01:39:02.298
I wish I could go, too.

1163
01:39:05.170 --> 01:39:06.171
(SONG ENDS)

1164
01:39:06.330 --> 01:39:07.331
(GUESTS APPLAUDING)

1165
01:39:11.930 --> 01:39:13.136
I must go.

1166
01:39:13.210 --> 01:39:16.100
Not before you've danced.
Both of you.


1167
01:39:16.210 --> 01:39:17.575
I insist.

1168
01:39:21.170 --> 01:39:22.854
Mr. Oak?

1169
01:39:25.290 --> 01:39:26.815
Thank you.
(SONG BEGINS)


1170
01:39:55.330 --> 01:39:57.332
Tell me what to do.

1171
01:40:02.210 --> 01:40:03.700
Gabriel?

1172
01:40:10.930 --> 01:40:12.773
Do what is right.

1173
01:40:16.650 --> 01:40:18.493
Sorry, excuse me.

1174
01:41:03.850 --> 01:41:05.340
(SOFTLY) Frank.

1175
01:41:06.770 --> 01:41:08.898
Black suits you.

1176
01:41:10.650 --> 01:41:12.812
Although a little premature.

1177
01:41:18.090 --> 01:41:19.933
You're alive.

1178
01:41:20.490 --> 01:41:24.176
And here I am.
Pulled from the sea.


1179
01:41:24.450 --> 01:41:27.818
Some fishermen found me
and brought me to shore.


1180
01:41:28.650 --> 01:41:31.017
Then I discovered I was dead
and found I preferred it.


1181
01:41:33.210 --> 01:41:34.860
For a while, anyway.

1182
01:41:35.130 --> 01:41:36.734
Why have you come back?

1183
01:41:36.890 --> 01:41:38.494
The strangest thing.

1184
01:41:39.690 --> 01:41:41.454
I missed you.

1185
01:41:43.090 --> 01:41:45.570
You don't seem very
happy to see me.


1186
01:41:45.850 --> 01:41:48.296
You said I was nothing to you.

1187
01:41:48.570 --> 01:41:49.935
(CHUCKLES) Did I?

1188
01:41:51.690 --> 01:41:56.173
Well, then.
Honesty at all times.


1189
01:41:56.930 --> 01:41:59.854
I find myself
in need of money.


1190
01:42:00.810 --> 01:42:02.175
I gave up
my profession for you,


1191
01:42:02.250 --> 01:42:04.059
and it seems a little harsh

1192
01:42:04.170 --> 01:42:05.410
that you have a farm
and a house


1193
01:42:05.450 --> 01:42:07.532
while I'm living off nothing.

1194
01:42:07.730 --> 01:42:09.095
There is no money.

1195
01:42:09.250 --> 01:42:10.695
Then sell the farm.

1196
01:42:22.530 --> 01:42:23.861
Come home.

1197
01:42:28.650 --> 01:42:30.140
No.

1198
01:42:32.250 --> 01:42:35.493
I said, come home.

1199
01:42:37.530 --> 01:42:40.181
I'm your husband
and you'll obey me!


1200
01:42:40.930 --> 01:42:41.931
(GUNSHOT)

1201
01:42:42.930 --> 01:42:44.534
(GASPS)

1202
01:42:56.970 --> 01:42:58.415
(SOFTLY) Oh, my God.

1203
01:44:25.370 --> 01:44:26.895
(FLOORBOARDS CREAKING)

1204
01:44:27.850 --> 01:44:29.534
BATHSHEBA: Let me see.

1205
01:44:32.290 --> 01:44:33.371
GABRIEL: If it's
any consolation,


1206
01:44:33.450 --> 01:44:35.293
his life will be spared.

1207
01:44:37.090 --> 01:44:38.774
Crime of passion.

1208
01:45:05.770 --> 01:45:07.340
Morning, Liddy.

1209
01:45:09.650 --> 01:45:11.414
COGGAN: It's a
fine harvest, ma'am.


1210
01:45:11.490 --> 01:45:12.935
Best we've had in years.

1211
01:45:13.050 --> 01:45:14.610
Will we have it all over
before the dew?


1212
01:45:14.650 --> 01:45:18.097
COGGAN: We will indeed, ma'am.
Luck's been on our side.


1213
01:45:23.930 --> 01:45:27.139
Come, Liddy,
give me a hand.


1214
01:45:30.650 --> 01:45:32.698
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

1215
01:45:49.650 --> 01:45:50.776
(CLEARS THROAT)

1216
01:45:51.370 --> 01:45:52.531
(BATHSHEBA CHUCKLES)

1217
01:45:52.610 --> 01:45:54.772
I'm sorry I startled you.

1218
01:45:56.450 --> 01:45:57.940
I wanted to
tidy up for them.


1219
01:45:58.010 --> 01:46:00.172
I haven't been here
for so long.


1220
01:46:03.290 --> 01:46:04.860
Are you going in?

1221
01:46:05.370 --> 01:46:08.533
Rehearsals.
I sing bass in the choir.


1222
01:46:08.850 --> 01:46:10.659
Yes, I've heard you.

1223
01:46:11.050 --> 01:46:13.815
(CHUCKLING)
Then I apologize.


1224
01:46:17.490 --> 01:46:20.334
I've been hoping to get
a chance to talk to you.


1225
01:46:21.130 --> 01:46:24.896
We've... We've not spoken
as much as I'd have liked.


1226
01:46:26.050 --> 01:46:27.415
No.

1227
01:46:36.050 --> 01:46:38.337
I'm leaving England.

1228
01:46:42.250 --> 01:46:43.740
Leaving?

1229
01:46:45.050 --> 01:46:47.052
Going to America.

1230
01:46:48.010 --> 01:46:50.490
There's a boat leaving
Bristol in four days' time.


1231
01:46:50.570 --> 01:46:52.095
I'll be on it.

1232
01:46:52.530 --> 01:46:54.214
Now that the farm is secure.

1233
01:46:55.410 --> 01:46:58.254
I understand I should
give you notice.


1234
01:47:00.410 --> 01:47:03.619
No. You must go
when you want.


1235
01:47:08.250 --> 01:47:10.537
I'll leave
first thing tomorrow.


1236
01:47:10.610 --> 01:47:12.055
No fuss.

1237
01:47:13.890 --> 01:47:15.255
I think that's best.

1238
01:47:58.570 --> 01:48:00.174
(OLD GEORGE WHIMPERING)

1239
01:48:07.890 --> 01:48:08.891
(SIGHING)

1240
01:48:13.330 --> 01:48:15.094
(OLD GEORGE YIPS)
(SIGHS)


1241
01:48:52.970 --> 01:48:54.540
(PANTING)

1242
01:49:02.490 --> 01:49:03.537
Gabriel!

1243
01:49:09.010 --> 01:49:10.341
Gabriel.

1244
01:49:11.210 --> 01:49:12.655
Wait.

1245
01:49:27.250 --> 01:49:28.490
(PANTING)

1246
01:49:30.330 --> 01:49:32.332
You'll think
I'm strange, but...


1247
01:49:33.850 --> 01:49:36.171
I've been worried.
Have I offended you somehow?


1248
01:49:36.250 --> 01:49:37.854
No, not at all.

1249
01:49:39.090 --> 01:49:40.660
Is it money?

1250
01:49:41.570 --> 01:49:43.254
I'll pay you
whatever you want.


1251
01:49:43.370 --> 01:49:45.179
I don't need money now.

1252
01:49:46.210 --> 01:49:47.735
A formal partnership, then?

1253
01:49:47.890 --> 01:49:49.380
Nor a partnership.

1254
01:49:50.370 --> 01:49:52.611
The farm belongs
to you alone.


1255
01:49:52.730 --> 01:49:55.017
It's the finest farm
for miles around.


1256
01:49:55.090 --> 01:49:57.172
Then why else are you leaving?

1257
01:49:57.250 --> 01:49:59.173
I said I'd
leave you one day.


1258
01:50:03.250 --> 01:50:05.617
Well, you must not go.

1259
01:50:06.530 --> 01:50:07.770
You forbid me?

1260
01:50:07.930 --> 01:50:09.261
Yes, if you like.
(CHUCKLES)


1261
01:50:09.930 --> 01:50:11.455
I forbid you.

1262
01:50:13.850 --> 01:50:16.774
It's time for you
to fight your own battles.


1263
01:50:17.610 --> 01:50:19.374
And win them, too.

1264
01:50:22.450 --> 01:50:24.418
So we should
say good-bye, then?


1265
01:50:25.890 --> 01:50:27.654
I suppose so.

1266
01:50:38.290 --> 01:50:39.655
Gabriel, wait.

1267
01:50:44.450 --> 01:50:46.179
Thank you, Gabriel.

1268
01:50:47.890 --> 01:50:50.291
You've believed in me
and fought for me


1269
01:50:51.290 --> 01:50:52.290
and stood by my side when

1270
01:50:52.330 --> 01:50:54.981
all the rest of the world
is against me.


1271
01:50:56.930 --> 01:50:59.331
And we've been through
so much together.


1272
01:51:04.010 --> 01:51:06.092
Wasn't I your
first sweetheart?


1273
01:51:08.810 --> 01:51:10.494
Weren't you mine?

1274
01:51:14.930 --> 01:51:16.341
(SIGHING)

1275
01:51:16.770 --> 01:51:19.535
And now I'd have to
go on without you.


1276
01:51:23.970 --> 01:51:25.972
If I knew...

1277
01:51:31.010 --> 01:51:32.455
If I knew
that you would


1278
01:51:32.530 --> 01:51:35.295
let me love you
and marry you...


1279
01:51:35.370 --> 01:51:37.179
But you will never know.

1280
01:51:39.170 --> 01:51:40.615
Why not?

1281
01:51:41.850 --> 01:51:44.171
Because you never ask!

1282
01:51:44.890 --> 01:51:46.733
Would you say no again?

1283
01:51:48.690 --> 01:51:50.021
I don't know.

1284
01:51:51.850 --> 01:51:53.375
Probably.

1285
01:51:54.370 --> 01:51:55.860
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1286
01:52:00.290 --> 01:52:02.133
So why don't you?

1287
01:52:03.890 --> 01:52:05.574
Ask me.

1288
01:52:09.650 --> 01:52:11.334
Ask me.

1289
01:52:15.890 --> 01:52:17.335
Ask me, Gabriel.